          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>Entity authority — consistent brand data across Wikidata, Wikipedia, LinkedIn, and directories — is the primary signal for base-model citation.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>Content structure matters: declarative opening statements, FAQ sections, and specific data points consistently outperform generic prose in citation likelihood.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>ChatGPT optimisation is distinct from Google AI Overview optimisation — different indexes and different retrieval mechanisms require platform-specific tactics.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1: How ChatGPT Sources Answers -->
      <section id="how-chatgpt-sources" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How ChatGPT Sources Answers</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>ChatGPT generates answers through two distinct mechanisms: parametric knowledge embedded in the model's weights, and real-time web retrieval via ChatGPT Search.</strong> Understanding which mechanism applies to your target queries is the starting point for any ChatGPT optimisation strategy.
        </p>

        <h3>Parametric Knowledge (Base Model)</h3>
        <p>
          When ChatGPT answers without browsing the web, it draws on information absorbed during training. The model was trained on a large corpus of web content, books, code, and other text, and its weights encode patterns about which brands, concepts, and facts are associated with which topics. A brand that is mentioned frequently in authoritative sources — Wikipedia, industry publications, research papers — within the training data is more likely to be recalled correctly when a user asks about its category.
        </p>
        <p>
          This matters because most ChatGPT queries are answered from parametric knowledge. Users on the free tier, users who have not enabled web browsing, and queries that the model judges can be answered without retrieval all fall into this mode. Your brand's parametric representation is a long-term asset that takes months to shift, but it is the citation mechanism that reaches the broadest ChatGPT user base.
        </p>

        <h3>The Role of Training Data Presence</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>The single most important factor for parametric citation is the volume and quality of authoritative sources that reference your brand.</strong> A brand mentioned accurately and consistently in Wikipedia articles, in trade press, in industry association directories, in academic papers, and in high-authority editorial content is more likely to appear in ChatGPT's parametric responses than a brand present only on its own website.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is not a process you can accelerate by submitting to directories or writing guest posts on low-quality blogs. Training data quality matters as much as volume. References in sources that were themselves well-represented in pre-training corpora — Wikipedia, The Guardian, TechCrunch, industry-specific publications — carry disproportionate weight.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: ChatGPT Search Explained -->
      <section id="chatgpt-search" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>ChatGPT Search Explained</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>ChatGPT Search is OpenAI's retrieval-augmented generation feature, enabling ChatGPT to retrieve live web pages and cite them as sources in its responses.</strong> It is available to ChatGPT Plus, Team, and Enterprise users, and represents the primary surface where real-time web content influences ChatGPT citations.
        </p>

        <p>
          When a user submits a query to ChatGPT Search, the system uses Bing's web index to retrieve a set of candidate pages. Those pages are read, summarised, and synthesised into the generated response, with clickable source citations. The process is broadly analogous to how Perplexity works, though the underlying retrieval infrastructure and model behaviour differ.
        </p>

        <h3>The Bing Connection</h3>
        <p>
          Because ChatGPT Search relies on Bing's index, the fundamentals of Bing SEO directly affect your ChatGPT Search visibility. Pages that are well-indexed in Bing, have strong domain authority in Bing's evaluation, and are technically accessible to Bing's crawlers are the candidates for retrieval. This means:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Verify your site is indexed in Bing Webmaster Tools — do not assume Google indexing equals Bing indexing.</li>
          <li>Submit your sitemap to Bing Webmaster Tools and resolve any crawl errors Bing reports.</li>
          <li>Bing tends to weight exact-match signals more heavily than Google — ensure your target terms appear in your page title, H1, and early body text.</li>
          <li>Bing has historically weighted social signals (LinkedIn, Twitter/X activity) more than Google; active brand presence on these platforms can support Bing authority.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>How ChatGPT Search Selects Sources</h3>
        <p>
          Within the retrieved candidate set, ChatGPT Search decides which pages to cite based on relevance and content quality. Pages that provide clear, extractable answers to the user's query — with declarative statements, structured headings, and specific claims — are more likely to be cited than pages with equivalent topical relevance but poor content structure. The model is effectively asking: "Does this page contain a passage I can accurately quote or paraphrase to answer this question?"
        </p>
        <p>
          This is where GEO content optimisation intersects with ChatGPT Search. Technical Bing visibility gets your pages into the retrieval candidate set; content structure determines whether those pages are actually cited.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: GPTBot & Crawling -->
      <section id="gptbot-crawling" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>GPTBot and AI Crawler Configuration</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>GPTBot is OpenAI's web crawler, and allowing it is a prerequisite for appearing in ChatGPT Search.</strong> If GPTBot is blocked in your robots.txt, OpenAI cannot retrieve your pages, and they will not appear as citations in ChatGPT Search responses regardless of how well they rank in Bing.
        </p>

        <h3>Checking Your Current robots.txt</h3>
        <p>
          Audit your <code>robots.txt</code> file (located at <code>yourdomain.com/robots.txt</code>) for any rules that block GPTBot. Common patterns to look for:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>User-agent: *</code> with <code>Disallow: /</code> — blocks all crawlers including GPTBot</li>
          <li><code>User-agent: GPTBot</code> with <code>Disallow: /</code> — explicit GPTBot block</li>
          <li>Disallow rules covering entire directories that contain your key content pages</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If you find blocking rules, you will need to add an explicit Allow rule or remove the block. The decision should be deliberate: allowing GPTBot grants OpenAI access to your content for both training data and search retrieval. Most brands aiming for ChatGPT visibility should allow GPTBot on their authoritative content pages. Sensitive pages, thin commercial pages, and content you would prefer not to feed into training data can be excluded selectively.
        </p>

        <h3>llms.txt as a Complementary Signal</h3>
        <p>
          Publishing an <code>llms.txt</code> file at the root of your domain provides AI crawlers with a curated guide to your site's most important content. It is not a replacement for robots.txt configuration, but it gives AI systems a prioritised entry point — useful when a crawler has limited crawl budget and you want it to reach your highest-value pages first.
        </p>
        <p>
          An effective llms.txt includes: your brand name and description, links to your key pillar pages, and a brief statement of your topical authority. For the current best practice specification, the proposal is documented at llmstxt.org, though implementation varies across AI platforms.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: 7-Step Optimisation Process -->
      <section id="optimisation-steps" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>7-Step ChatGPT Optimisation Process</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Getting cited in ChatGPT requires a systematic approach addressing crawl access, entity authority, content structure, and ongoing monitoring.</strong> These seven steps cover the full process.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
          <div class="card p-5 flex gap-4">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">01</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50 mb-1">Audit current ChatGPT visibility</h3>
              <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Open ChatGPT with web browsing enabled. Run your top 20 target queries — the questions your customers ask when researching your category. Record whether your brand appears, whether it is cited accurately, and which competitors are mentioned instead. This baseline tells you where the gaps are before you invest in any changes.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5 flex gap-4">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">02</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50 mb-1">Fix robots.txt to allow GPTBot</h3>
              <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Audit robots.txt and remove any rules that block GPTBot. Add selective Allow rules for your key content pages if needed. Verify the change with a robots.txt tester. Submit your updated sitemap to Bing Webmaster Tools to trigger re-crawling.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5 flex gap-4">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">03</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50 mb-1">Verify and improve Bing indexation</h3>
              <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Log in to Bing Webmaster Tools and confirm your key pages are indexed. Resolve any crawl errors. Submit your XML sitemap if you have not already. Bing indexation is a prerequisite for ChatGPT Search retrieval — it is a separate system from Google Search Console and requires its own setup.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5 flex gap-4">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">04</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50 mb-1">Build entity authority</h3>
              <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Establish and maintain consistent entity data across Wikipedia (where notability criteria are met), Wikidata, Crunchbase, LinkedIn, Companies House, and relevant industry directories. Add <code>sameAs</code> references in your Organisation schema pointing to each of these records. Consistency in your brand name, description, and classification across all sources reduces entity ambiguity and strengthens parametric citation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5 flex gap-4">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">05</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50 mb-1">Restructure content for citability</h3>
              <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Audit your key pages against the citability criteria below. Lead every major section with a bold declarative sentence. Add structured FAQ sections with self-contained answers. Include at least one table, one numbered list, and specific data points on each key page. Remove vague language and marketing copy that adds no extractable information. This is the highest-leverage change for ChatGPT Search citation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5 flex gap-4">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">06</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50 mb-1">Implement and validate JSON-LD schema</h3>
              <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Deploy Article, FAQPage, HowTo (where relevant), and Organisation schema with complete <code>sameAs</code> references. Use the Schema.org Markup Validator and Google's Rich Results Test to confirm validity. Schema reduces ambiguity in retrieval-augmented pipelines and provides a machine-readable summary of your page's claims — useful even where the model does not rely on structured data as a primary ranking signal.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5 flex gap-4">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">07</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50 mb-1">Monitor, measure, and iterate</h3>
              <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Re-run your query set monthly. Track citation frequency, citation accuracy, and share of voice versus competitors. When a competitor is cited and you are not, analyse their page for the structural or authority differences that explain the gap. Refine the content that does get cited to maintain its citability as you expand to new query sets. ChatGPT's model and feature updates mean regular re-testing is essential — what works today may behave differently after a model update.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: Content That Gets Cited -->
      <section id="content-for-chatgpt" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Content That Gets Cited by ChatGPT</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>ChatGPT demonstrates clear preferences for specific content structures when selecting passages to include in generated responses.</strong> These patterns apply to both ChatGPT Search (retrieval-based) and, to a lesser extent, the base model's handling of queries where it draws on its training data.
        </p>

        <h3>Declarative Opening Statements</h3>
        <p>
          The most consistently cited content pattern is the declarative opening statement: a sentence at the start of a section that defines a concept, names a process, or states a fact directly. "Generative Engine Optimisation is the practice of..." is far more likely to be extracted and cited than "Many businesses are now considering how to approach the world of AI search, which has changed significantly in recent years." Lead with the answer; provide context second.
        </p>

        <h3>Specific, Named Data Points</h3>
        <p>
          ChatGPT cites content that contains specific, verifiable claims: a percentage figure, a named study, a defined methodology, a specific date or version number. Generic assertions are paraphrased or ignored. Proprietary data or original research is particularly valuable — if your source is the only place a specific fact appears, ChatGPT's retrieval system has no choice but to cite you for it.
        </p>

        <h3>Self-Contained FAQ Answers</h3>
        <p>
          FAQ sections with explicit question-answer pairs are among the most reliably cited content structures. Each answer should function as a standalone unit — readable and meaningful without surrounding context. Pair FAQ content with FAQPage schema for maximum structured signal. This pattern directly maps onto the "user asks a question, ChatGPT provides an answer with source" citation format.
        </p>

        <h3>Tables and Structured Comparisons</h3>
        <p>
          When users ask ChatGPT to compare options, the model draws heavily on comparison tables it has retrieved. A well-structured HTML table with clear column headers and definitive cell values gives ChatGPT a clean data structure to extract and reproduce. Tables also signal topical expertise to the retrieval system — a page that contains a detailed comparison table on a subject is implicitly authoritative on that subject.
        </p>
      </section>

